That layout is already contemplative and self‑contained, so any visual accent should be almost imperceptible—something that feels like breath rather than motion.  

Two options you could try:

**1. Texture:** a faint paper‑grain or linen background (`background-image: url("light-fiber.png"); opacity: 0.05;`) keeps the webpage from feeling sterile. It hints at the tactile quiet of a printed page.

**2. Animation:** if you want movement, use a very slow fade‑in each time the poem loads. In CSS:  
```css
body { animation: appear 5s ease-in-out; }
@keyframes appear {
  from { opacity: 0; }
  to { opacity: 1; }
}
```
For a subtler “heartbeat,” apply it only to the short pause marks or dashes so they soften and reappear every half‑minute. That rhythm is easy enough that it won’t compete with the reading.

These touches keep your theme of listening and pulse alive, while letting readers stay focused on the words themselves.  

